    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-10T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-10T03:00:00-05:00" n="682"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d682">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9315 Manchuria/229: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-10T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 10, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>653. <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi>
                    <note n="33" xml:id="d682fn33">Official organ of the Central Committee and
                        Moscow Committee of the All-Union Communist Party.</note> this morning
                    publishes the following Foreign Office statement:<note n="34" xml:id="d682fn34"
                        >A press release was also issued at Tokyo by the Japanese Foreign
                        Office.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“As a result of negotiations which have recently taken place between V.
                            M. Molotov, the People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs, and Mr. Togo,
                            the Japanese Ambassador, with respect to mutual recognition of the
                            interests of both the Soviet-Mongolian and the Japanese-Man-chukuo
                            parties, which have come to an understanding, an agreement was reached
                            on June 9 concerning the question of delineation of the boundary in the
                            region of last year’s conflict, a question which was not decided by the
                            Soviet-Mongolian and Japanese-Manchukuo mixed commission for delineation
                            of the boundary in the said region and which constituted an obstacle to
                            the regulation of relations between the United States and<note n="35"
                                xml:id="d682fn35">The words “United States and” were apparently
                                inserted by mistake.</note> U. S. S. R. and Japan as well as between
                            the Mongolian People’s Republic and Manchukuo.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Repeat to Embassy at Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
